        <mj-text css-class="article">
          <h2>Stuff &amp; Things</h2>
          <p>Our curated list of recent, suggested listening, reading and viewing.</p>
          <dl>
            <dt><a href="https://petapixel.com/2022/12/08/photographer-loses-plagarism-case-against-artist-who-ripped-off-her-work/">Luxembourg court fails to uphold photographer's copyright</a></dt>
            <dd>Jinga Zhang is a fashion photographer whose work I have been following for something like 15 years. The images she creates are simply gorgeous, and most definitely have a signature quality all her own. And so this ruling by Luxembourg courts not to protect her copyright in the face of blatant infringement is simply galling.</dd>
            <dd>Jinga Zhang has been deeply distressed by the decision, evident by her Instagram posts, <a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/Cl3y9GFrhdm/?hl=en">here</a> and <a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/CmDsJWmDr5O/?hl=en">here</a>.
            
            <dt><a href="https://youtu.be/qMWAY8Cdsz0">I Have to Pirate COLOURS Now??</a></dt>
            <dd>Linus Tech Tips goes deep into the Adobe vs. Pantone licensing debacle. Along the way, he also talks about how subscription-based software kinda sucks.</dd>

            <dt><a href="https://kotaku.com/adobe-ai-generated-art-photoshop-stock-bad-sucks-1849880495">Adobe Embraces AI Art</a> (╬≖_≖)</dt>
            <dd>From Kotaku, a less than charitable take on Adobe's inclusion of A.I. generated art in its collection of stock images.</dd>
            <dd>Personally, I've had fun tinkering with A.I. art generators; they are highly entertaining! But would never try to sell or pass off any such creations as real art, and cannot think of any commercial context in which I would try or want to use them, except maybe as dressing for a blog post(?).</dd>

            <dt><a href="">Guillermo del Toro says AI art used in film would be "an insult to life itself"</a></dt>
            <dd>From Polygon; Guillermo del Toro says, "I consume and love art made by humans".</dd>

            <dt><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y2QV4kNHCrE">Is Imitation Vanilla Actually Better than Real Vanilla?</a></dt>
            <dd>We've been pretty down on Adobe, A.I., and imitations in this batch of links, so here's a thematically appropriate palate cleanser from one of my favorite culinary shows, "What's Eating Dan?"</dd>
            
            <dt><a href="https://petapixel.com/2022/12/07/capture-ones-actions-say-perpetual-software-just-isnt-profitable-enough/">Capture One’s Actions Say Perpetual Software Just isn’t Profitable Enough</a></dt>
            <dd>It's not just Adobe breaking my heart these days. Capture One, my favorite photo software for a long while now, has been pretty disappointing with its last couple of versions, and their newly announced licensing changes are ripe BS. Not sure what I'm going to do, but will wait for details about their "loyalty scheme" to make a decision.</dd>

            <dt><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E4eX0ZLgfQo">Why Gordon Parks' Most Famous Photo Almost Wasn't Released</a></dt>
            <dd>PBS' The Bigger Picture with Vincent Brown takes a deeper look at Gordon Parks' iconic image, "American Gothic", and the larger power of photography.</dd>
            
            <dt><a href="https://pod.link/bjork">Björk: Sonic Symbolism</a></dt>
            <dd>In our previous edition, the Music Pick was a track from Björk's new album, <cite>Fossora</cite>. In this podcast, Björk walks us through each of her magnificent albums, one per episode, shedding light on the influences and inspirations that have charted her musical path. I love this.</dd> 
            
            <dt><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yHwKSosF_QE">Music Pick: "replay!" by Kimbra</a></dt>
            <dd>Mildly NSFW video, featuring Kimbra at her most sexually suggestive. But the song is a banger, about being stuck in a mental/emotional replay loop following a breakup. Kimbra's upcoming album is currently the new music I am most looking forward to in 2023. She discusses this song and more in depth in <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LsEbpKrZe9s">this interview</a>.</dd>
          </dl>
        </mj-text>        
